Q. What is BiConsumer?

Ans: Let's start with basic first:-

1️⃣ Consumer (Consumes ONE thing)

🧠 Meaning
Takes one input, returns nothing

Syntax:
Consumer<T>

Method:
void accept(T t);

Example:

Consumer<String> print =
        s -> System.out.println(s);

print.accept("Hello");

📌 Used when you want to do something, not return something.

2️⃣ BiConsumer (Consumes TWO things)

🧠 Meaning
Takes two inputs, returns nothing

Syntax:
BiConsumer<T, U>

Method:
void accept(T t, U u);

Example:
BiConsumer<String, Integer> print =
        (name, age) -> System.out.println(name + " " + age);

print.accept("Tanisha", 23);

3️⃣ Where Consumer / BiConsumer Are Used

(i) Streams:
list.forEach(e -> System.out.println(e));   // Consumer

(ii) Map:
map.forEach((k, v) -> System.out.println(k + "=" + v)); // BiConsumer